091Sm 14:3 among whom was Ahijah, who was wearing an ephod. He was a son of Ichabod's brother Ahitub son of Phinehas, the son of Eli, the LORD'S priest in Shiloh. No one was aware that Jonathan had left.
091Sm 14:4 On each side of the pass that Jonathan intended to cross to reach the Philistine outpost was a cliff; one was called Bozez, and the other Seneh.
091Sm 14:5 One cliff stood to the north toward Micmash, the other to the south toward Geba.
091Sm 14:6 Jonathan said to his young armor-bearer, "Come, let's go over to the outpost of those uncircumcised fellows. Perhaps the LORD will act in our behalf. Nothing can hinder the LORD from saving, whether by many or by few."
091Sm 14:7 "Do all that you have in mind," his armor-bearer said. "Go ahead; I am with you heart and soul."
091Sm 14:8 Jonathan said, "Come, then; we will cross over toward the men and let them see us.
091Sm 14:9 If they say to us, 'Wait there until we come to you,' we will stay where we are and not go up to them.
091Sm 14:10 But if they say, 'Come up to us,' we will climb up, because that will be our sign that the LORD has given them into our hands."
091Sm 14:11 So both of them showed themselves to the Philistine outpost. "Look!" said the Philistines. "The Hebrews are crawling out of the holes they were hiding in."
091Sm 14:12 The men of the outpost shouted to Jonathan and his armor-bearer, "Come up to us and we'll teach you a lesson." So Jonathan said to his armor-bearer, "Climb up after me; the LORD has given them into the hand of Israel."
091Sm 14:13 Jonathan climbed up, using his hands and feet, with his armor-bearer right behind him. The Philistines fell before Jonathan, and his armor-bearer followed and killed behind him.
091Sm 14:14 In that first attack Jonathan and his armor-bearer killed some twenty men in an area of about half an acre.
091Sm 14:15 Then panic struck the whole army--those in the camp and field, and those in the outposts and raiding parties--and the ground shook. It was a panic sent by God.
091Sm 14:16 Saul's lookouts at Gibeah in Benjamin saw the army melting away in all directions.
091Sm 14:17 Then Saul said to the men who were with him, "Muster the forces and see who has left us." When they did, it was Jonathan and his armor-bearer who were not there.
091Sm 14:18 Saul said to Ahijah, "Bring the ark of God." (At that time it was with the Israelites.)
091Sm 14:19 While Saul was talking to the priest, the tumult in the Philistine camp increased more and more. So Saul said to the priest, "Withdraw your hand."
091Sm 14:20 Then Saul and all his men assembled and went to the battle. They found the Philistines in total confusion, striking each other with their swords.
091Sm 14:21 Those Hebrews who had previously been with the Philistines and had gone up with them to their camp went over to the Israelites who were with Saul and Jonathan.
091Sm 14:22 When all the Israelites who had hidden in the hill country of Ephraim heard that the Philistines were on the run, they joined the battle in hot pursuit.
091Sm 14:23 So the LORD rescued Israel that day, and the battle moved on beyond Beth Aven.
091Sm 14:24 Now the men of Israel were in distress that day, because Saul had bound the people under an oath, saying, "Cursed be any man who eats food before evening comes, before I have avenged myself on my enemies!" So none of the troops tasted food.
091Sm 14:25 The entire army entered the woods, and there was honey on the ground.
091Sm 14:26 When they went into the woods, they saw the honey oozing out, yet no one put his hand to his mouth, because they feared the oath.
091Sm 14:27 But Jonathan had not heard that his father had bound the people with the oath, so he reached out the end of the staff that was in his hand and dipped it into the honeycomb. He raised his hand to his mouth, and his eyes brightened.
091Sm 14:28 Then one of the soldiers told him, "Your father bound the army under a strict oath, saying, 'Cursed be any man who eats food today!' That is why the men are faint."
091Sm 14:29 Jonathan said, "My father has made trouble for the country. See how my eyes brightened when I tasted a little of this honey.
091Sm 14:30 How much better it would have been if the men had eaten today some of the plunder they took from their enemies. Would not the slaughter of the Philistines have been even greater?"
091Sm 14:31 That day, after the Israelites had struck down the Philistines from Micmash to Aijalon, they were exhausted.
091Sm 14:32 They pounced on the plunder and, taking sheep, cattle and calves, they butchered them on the ground and ate them, together with the blood.
091Sm 14:33 Then someone said to Saul, "Look, the men are sinning against the LORD by eating meat that has blood in it." "You have broken faith," he said. "Roll a large stone over here at once."
091Sm 14:34 Then he said, "Go out among the men and tell them, 'Each of you bring me your cattle and sheep, and slaughter them here and eat them. Do not sin against the LORD by eating meat with blood still in it.'" So everyone brought his ox that night and slaughtered it there.
091Sm 14:35 Then Saul built an altar to the LORD; it was the first time he had done this.
091Sm 14:36 Saul said, "Let us go down after the Philistines by night and plunder them till dawn, and let us not leave one of them alive." "Do whatever seems best to you," they replied. But the priest said, "Let us inquire of God here."
091Sm 14:37 So Saul asked God, "Shall I go down after the Philistines? Will you give them into Israel's hand?" But God did not answer him that day.
091Sm 14:38 Saul therefore said, "Come here, all you who are leaders of the army, and let us find out what sin has been committed today.
091Sm 14:39 As surely as the LORD who rescues Israel lives, even if it lies with my son Jonathan, he must die." But not one of the men said a word.
091Sm 14:40 Saul then said to all the Israelites, "You stand over there; I and Jonathan my son will stand over here." "Do what seems best to you," the men replied.
091Sm 14:41 Then Saul prayed to the LORD, the God of Israel, "Give me the right answer." And Jonathan and Saul were taken by lot, and the men were cleared.
091Sm 14:42 Saul said, "Cast the lot between me and Jonathan my son." And Jonathan was taken.
091Sm 14:43 Then Saul said to Jonathan, "Tell me what you have done." So Jonathan told him, "I merely tasted a little honey with the end of my staff. And now must I die?"
091Sm 14:44 Saul said, "May God deal with me, be it ever so severely, if you do not die, Jonathan."
091Sm 14:45 But the men said to Saul, "Should Jonathan die--he who has brought about this great deliverance in Israel? Never! As surely as the LORD lives, not a hair of his head will fall to the ground, for he did this today with God's help." So the men rescued Jonathan, and he was not put to death.
091Sm 14:46 Then Saul stopped pursuing the Philistines, and they withdrew to their own land.
091Sm 14:47 After Saul had assumed rule over Israel, he fought against their enemies on every side£º Moab, the Ammonites, Edom, the kings of Zobah, and the Philistines. Wherever he turned, he inflicted punishment on them.
091Sm 14:48 He fought valiantly and defeated the Amalekites, delivering Israel from the hands of those who had plundered them.
091Sm 14:49 Saul's sons were Jonathan, Ishvi and Malki-Shua. The name of his older daughter was Merab, and that of the younger was Michal.
091Sm 14:50 His wife's name was Ahinoam daughter of Ahimaaz. The name of the commander of Saul's army was Abner son of Ner, and Ner was Saul's uncle.
091Sm 14:51 Saul's father Kish and Abner's father Ner were sons of Abiel.
091Sm 14:52 All the days of Saul there was bitter war with the Philistines, and whenever Saul saw a mighty or brave man, he took him into his service.
091Sm 15:1 Samuel said to Saul, "I am the one the LORD sent to anoint you king over his people Israel; so listen now to the message from the LORD.
091Sm 15:2 This is what the LORD Almighty says£º 'I will punish the Amalekites for what they did to Israel when they waylaid them as they came up from Egypt.
091Sm 15:3 Now go, attack the Amalekites and totally destroy everything that belongs to them. Do not spare them; put to death men and women, children and infants, cattle and sheep, camels and donkeys.'"
091Sm 15:4 So Saul summoned the men and mustered them at Telaim--two hundred thousand foot soldiers and ten thousand men from Judah.
091Sm 15:5 Saul went to the city of Amalek and set an ambush in the ravine.
091Sm 15:6 Then he said to the Kenites, "Go away, leave the Amalekites so that I do not destroy you along with them; for you showed kindness to all the Israelites when they came up out of Egypt." So the Kenites moved away from the Amalekites.
091Sm 15:7 Then Saul attacked the Amalekites all the way from Havilah to Shur, to the east of Egypt.
091Sm 15:8 He took Agag king of the Amalekites alive, and all his people he totally destroyed with the sword.
091Sm 15:9 But Saul and the army spared Agag and the best of the sheep and cattle, the fat calves and lambs--everything that was good. These they were unwilling to destroy completely, but everything that was despised and weak they totally destroyed.
091Sm 15:10 Then the word of the LORD came to Samuel£º
091Sm 15:11 "I am grieved that I have made Saul king, because he has turned away from me and has not carried out my instructions." Samuel was troubled, and he cried out to the LORD all that night.
091Sm 15:12 Early in the morning Samuel got up and went to meet Saul, but he was told, "Saul has gone to Carmel. There he has set up a monument in his own honor and has turned and gone on down to Gilgal."
091Sm 15:13 When Samuel reached him, Saul said, "The LORD bless you! I have carried out the LORD'S instructions."
091Sm 15:14 But Samuel said, "What then is this bleating of sheep in my ears? What is this lowing of cattle that I hear?"
091Sm 15:15 Saul answered, "The soldiers brought them from the Amalekites; they spared the best of the sheep and cattle to sacrifice to the LORD your God, but we totally destroyed the rest."
091Sm 15:16 "Stop!" Samuel said to Saul. "Let me tell you what the LORD said to me last night." "Tell me," Saul replied.
091Sm 15:17 Samuel said, "Although you were once small in your own eyes, did you not become the head of the tribes of Israel? The LORD anointed you king over Israel.
091Sm 15:18 And he sent you on a mission, saying, 'Go and completely destroy those wicked people, the Amalekites; make war on them until you have wiped them out.'
091Sm 15:19 Why did you not obey the LORD? Why did you pounce on the plunder and do evil in the eyes of the LORD?"
091Sm 15:20 "But I did obey the LORD," Saul said. "I went on the mission the LORD assigned me. I completely destroyed the Amalekites and brought back Agag their king.
091Sm 15:21 The soldiers took sheep and cattle from the plunder, the best of what was devoted to God, in order to sacrifice them to the LORD your God at Gilgal."
091Sm 15:22 But Samuel replied£º "Does the LORD delight in burnt offerings and sacrifices as much as in obeying the voice of the LORD? To obey is better than sacrifice, and to heed is better than the fat of rams.
091Sm 15:23 For rebellion is like the sin of divination, and arrogance like the evil of idolatry. Because you have rejected the word of the LORD, he has rejected you as king."
091Sm 15:24 Then Saul said to Samuel, "I have sinned. I violated the LORD'S command and your instructions. I was afraid of the people and so I gave in to them.
091Sm 15:25 Now I beg you, forgive my sin and come back with me, so that I may worship the LORD."
091Sm 15:26 But Samuel said to him, "I will not go back with you. You have rejected the word of the LORD, and the LORD has rejected you as king over Israel!"
091Sm 15:27 As Samuel turned to leave, Saul caught hold of the hem of his robe, and it tore.
091Sm 15:28 Samuel said to him, "The LORD has torn the kingdom of Israel from you today and has given it to one of your neighbors--to one better than you.
091Sm 15:29 He who is the Glory of Israel does not lie or change his mind; for he is not a man, that he should change his mind."
091Sm 15:30 Saul replied, "I have sinned. But please honor me before the elders of my people and before Israel; come back with me, so that I may worship the LORD your God."
091Sm 15:31 So Samuel went back with Saul, and Saul worshiped the LORD.
091Sm 15:32 Then Samuel said, "Bring me Agag king of the Amalekites." Agag came to him confidently, thinking, "Surely the bitterness of death is past."
091Sm 15:33 But Samuel said, "As your sword has made women childless, so will your mother be childless among women." And Samuel put Agag to death before the LORD at Gilgal.
091Sm 15:34 Then Samuel left for Ramah, but Saul went up to his home in Gibeah of Saul.
091Sm 15:35 Until the day Samuel died, he did not go to see Saul again, though Samuel mourned for him. And the LORD was grieved that he had made Saul king over Israel.
091Sm 16:1 The LORD said to Samuel, "How long will you mourn for Saul, since I have rejected him as king over Israel? Fill your horn with oil and be on your way; I am sending you to Jesse of Bethlehem. I have chosen one of his sons to be king."
091Sm 16:2 But Samuel said, "How can I go? Saul will hear about it and kill me." The LORD said, "Take a heifer with you and say, 'I have come to sacrifice to the LORD.'
091Sm 16:3 Invite Jesse to the sacrifice, and I will show you what to do. You are to anoint for me the one I indicate."
091Sm 16:4 Samuel did what the LORD said. When he arrived at Bethlehem, the elders of the town trembled when they met him. They asked, "Do you come in peace?"
091Sm 16:5 Samuel replied, "Yes, in peace; I have come to sacrifice to the LORD. Consecrate yourselves and come to the sacrifice with me." Then he consecrated Jesse and his sons and invited them to the sacrifice.
091Sm 16:6 When they arrived, Samuel saw Eliab and thought, "Surely the LORD'S anointed stands here before the LORD."
091Sm 16:7 But the LORD said to Samuel, "Do not consider his appearance or his height, for I have rejected him. The LORD does not look at the things man looks at. Man looks at the outward appearance, but the LORD looks at the heart."
091Sm 16:8 Then Jesse called Abinadab and had him pass in front of Samuel. But Samuel said, "The LORD has not chosen this one either."
091Sm 16:9 Jesse then had Shammah pass by, but Samuel said, "Nor has the LORD chosen this one."
091Sm 16:10 Jesse had seven of his sons pass before Samuel, but Samuel said to him, "The LORD has not chosen these."
091Sm 16:11 So he asked Jesse, "Are these all the sons you have?" "There is still the youngest," Jesse answered, "but he is tending the sheep." Samuel said, "Send for him; we will not sit down until he arrives."
091Sm 16:12 So he sent and had him brought in. He was ruddy, with a fine appearance and handsome features. Then the LORD said, "Rise and anoint him; he is the one."
091Sm 16:13 So Samuel took the horn of oil and anointed him in the presence of his brothers, and from that day on the Spirit of the LORD came upon David in power. Samuel then went to Ramah.
091Sm 16:14 Now the Spirit of the LORD had departed from Saul, and an evil spirit from the LORD tormented him.
091Sm 16:15 Saul's attendants said to him, "See, an evil spirit from God is tormenting you.
091Sm 16:16 Let our lord command his servants here to search for someone who can play the harp. He will play when the evil spirit from God comes upon you, and you will feel better."
091Sm 16:17 So Saul said to his attendants, "Find someone who plays well and bring him to me."
091Sm 16:18 One of the servants answered, "I have seen a son of Jesse of Bethlehem who knows how to play the harp. He is a brave man and a warrior. He speaks well and is a fine-looking man. And the LORD is with him."
091Sm 16:19 Then Saul sent messengers to Jesse and said, "Send me your son David, who is with the sheep."
091Sm 16:20 So Jesse took a donkey loaded with bread, a skin of wine and a young goat and sent them with his son David to Saul.
091Sm 16:21 David came to Saul and entered his service. Saul liked him very much, and David became one of his armor-bearers.
091Sm 16:22 Then Saul sent word to Jesse, saying, "Allow David to remain in my service, for I am pleased with him."
091Sm 16:23 Whenever the spirit from God came upon Saul, David would take his harp and play. Then relief would come to Saul; he would feel better, and the evil spirit would leave him.
091Sm 17:1 Now the Philistines gathered their forces for war and assembled at Socoh in Judah. They pitched camp at Ephes Dammim, between Socoh and Azekah.
091Sm 17:2 Saul and the Israelites assembled and camped in the Valley of Elah and drew up their battle line to meet the Philistines.
091Sm 17:3 The Philistines occupied one hill and the Israelites another, with the valley between them.
091Sm 17:4 A champion named Goliath, who was from Gath, came out of the Philistine camp. He was over nine feet tall.
091Sm 17:5 He had a bronze helmet on his head and wore a coat of scale armor of bronze weighing five thousand shekels;
091Sm 17:6 on his legs he wore bronze greaves, and a bronze javelin was slung on his back.
091Sm 17:7 His spear shaft was like a weaver's rod, and its iron point weighed six hundred shekels. His shield bearer went ahead of him.
091Sm 17:8 Goliath stood and shouted to the ranks of Israel, "Why do you come out and line up for battle? Am I not a Philistine, and are you not the servants of Saul? Choose a man and have him come down to me.
091Sm 17:9 If he is able to fight and kill me, we will become your subjects; but if I overcome him and kill him, you will become our subjects and serve us."
091Sm 17:10 Then the Philistine said, "This day I defy the ranks of Israel! Give me a man and let us fight each other."
091Sm 17:11 On hearing the Philistine's words, Saul and all the Israelites were dismayed and terrified.
091Sm 17:12 Now David was the son of an Ephrathite named Jesse, who was from Bethlehem in Judah. Jesse had eight sons, and in Saul's time he was old and well advanced in years.
091Sm 17:13 Jesse's three oldest sons had followed Saul to the war£º The firstborn was Eliab; the second, Abinadab; and the third, Shammah.
091Sm 17:14 David was the youngest. The three oldest followed Saul,
091Sm 17:15 but David went back and forth from Saul to tend his father's sheep at Bethlehem.
091Sm 17:16 For forty days the Philistine came forward every morning and evening and took his stand.
091Sm 17:17 Now Jesse said to his son David, "Take this ephah of roasted grain and these ten loaves of bread for your brothers and hurry to their camp.
091Sm 17:18 Take along these ten cheeses to the commander of their unit. See how your brothers are and bring back some assurance from them.
091Sm 17:19 They are with Saul and all the men of Israel in the Valley of Elah, fighting against the Philistines."
091Sm 17:20 Early in the morning David left the flock with a shepherd, loaded up and set out, as Jesse had directed. He reached the camp as the army was going out to its battle positions, shouting the war cry.
091Sm 17:21 Israel and the Philistines were drawing up their lines facing each other.
091Sm 17:22 David left his things with the keeper of supplies, ran to the battle lines and greeted his brothers.
091Sm 17:23 As he was talking with them, Goliath, the Philistine champion from Gath, stepped out from his lines and shouted his usual defiance, and David heard it.
091Sm 17:24 When the Israelites saw the man, they all ran from him in great fear.
091Sm 17:25 Now the Israelites had been saying, "Do you see how this man keeps coming out? He comes out to defy Israel. The king will give great wealth to the man who kills him. He will also give him his daughter in marriage and will exempt his father's family from taxes in Israel."
091Sm 17:26 David asked the men standing near him, "What will be done for the man who kills this Philistine and removes this disgrace from Israel? Who is this uncircumcised Philistine that he should defy the armies of the living God?"
091Sm 17:27 They repeated to him what they had been saying and told him, "This is what will be done for the man who kills him."
091Sm 17:28 When Eliab, David's oldest brother, heard him speaking with the men, he burned with anger at him and asked, "Why have you come down here? And with whom did you leave those few sheep in the desert? I know how conceited you are and how wicked your heart is; you came down only to watch the battle."
091Sm 17:29 "Now what have I done?" said David. "Can't I even speak?"
091Sm 17:30 He then turned away to someone else and brought up the same matter, and the men answered him as before.
091Sm 17:31 What David said was overheard and reported to Saul, and Saul sent for him.
091Sm 17:32 David said to Saul, "Let no one lose heart on account of this Philistine; your servant will go and fight him."
091Sm 17:33 Saul replied, "You are not able to go out against this Philistine and fight him; you are only a boy, and he has been a fighting man from his youth."
091Sm 17:34 But David said to Saul, "Your servant has been keeping his father's sheep. When a lion or a bear came and carried off a sheep from the flock,
091Sm 17:35 I went after it, struck it and rescued the sheep from its mouth. When it turned on me, I seized it by its hair, struck it and killed it.
091Sm 17:36 Your servant has killed both the lion and the bear; this uncircumcised Philistine will be like one of them, because he has defied the armies of the living God.
091Sm 17:37 The LORD who delivered me from the paw of the lion and the paw of the bear will deliver me from the hand of this Philistine." Saul said to David, "Go, and the LORD be with you."
091Sm 17:38 Then Saul dressed David in his own tunic. He put a coat of armor on him and a bronze helmet on his head.
091Sm 17:39 David fastened on his sword over the tunic and tried walking around, because he was not used to them. "I cannot go in these," he said to Saul, "because I am not used to them." So he took them off.
091Sm 17:40 Then he took his staff in his hand, chose five smooth stones from the stream, put them in the pouch of his shepherd's bag and, with his sling in his hand, approached the Philistine.
091Sm 17:41 Meanwhile, the Philistine, with his shield bearer in front of him, kept coming closer to David.
091Sm 17:42 He looked David over and saw that he was only a boy, ruddy and handsome, and he despised him.
091Sm 17:43 He said to David, "Am I a dog, that you come at me with sticks?" And the Philistine cursed David by his gods.
091Sm 17:44 "Come here," he said, "and I'll give your flesh to the birds of the air and the beasts of the field!"
091Sm 17:45 David said to the Philistine, "You come against me with sword and spear and javelin, but I come against you in the name of the LORD Almighty, the God of the armies of Israel, whom you have defied.
091Sm 17:46 This day the LORD will hand you over to me, and I'll strike you down and cut off your head. Today I will give the carcasses of the Philistine army to the birds of the air and the beasts of the earth, and the whole world will know that there is a God in Israel.
091Sm 17:47 All those gathered here will know that it is not by sword or spear that the LORD saves; for the battle is the LORD'S, and he will give all of you into our hands."
091Sm 17:48 As the Philistine moved closer to attack him, David ran quickly toward the battle line to meet him.
091Sm 17:49 Reaching into his bag and taking out a stone, he slung it and struck the Philistine on the forehead. The stone sank into his forehead, and he fell facedown on the ground.
091Sm 17:50 So David triumphed over the Philistine with a sling and a stone; without a sword in his hand he struck down the Philistine and killed him.
091Sm 17:51 David ran and stood over him. He took hold of the Philistine's sword and drew it from the scabbard. After he killed him, he cut off his head with the sword. When the Philistines saw that their hero was dead, they turned and ran.
091Sm 17:52 Then the men of Israel and Judah surged forward with a shout and pursued the Philistines to the entrance of Gath and to the gates of Ekron. Their dead were strewn along the Shaaraim road to Gath and Ekron.
091Sm 17:53 When the Israelites returned from chasing the Philistines, they plundered their camp.
091Sm 17:54 David took the Philistine's head and brought it to Jerusalem, and he put the Philistine's weapons in his own tent.
091Sm 17:55 As Saul watched David going out to meet the Philistine, he said to Abner, commander of the army, "Abner, whose son is that young man?" Abner replied, "As surely as you live, O king, I don't know."
091Sm 17:56 The king said, "Find out whose son this young man is."
091Sm 17:57 As soon as David returned from killing the Philistine, Abner took him and brought him before Saul, with David still holding the Philistine's head.
091Sm 17:58 "Whose son are you, young man?" Saul asked him. David said, "I am the son of your servant Jesse of Bethlehem."
091Sm 18:1 After David had finished talking with Saul, Jonathan became one in spirit with David, and he loved him as himself.
091Sm 18:2 From that day Saul kept David with him and did not let him return to his father's house.
091Sm 18:3 And Jonathan made a covenant with David because he loved him as himself.
091Sm 18:4 Jonathan took off the robe he was wearing and gave it to David, along with his tunic, and even his sword, his bow and his belt.
091Sm 18:5 Whatever Saul sent him to do, David did it so successfully that Saul gave him a high rank in the army. This pleased all the people, and Saul's officers as well.
091Sm 18:6 When the men were returning home after David had killed the Philistine, the women came out from all the towns of Israel to meet King Saul with singing and dancing, with joyful songs and with tambourines and lutes.
091Sm 18:7 As they danced, they sang£º "Saul has slain his thousands, and David his tens of thousands."
091Sm 18:8 Saul was very angry; this refrain galled him. "They have credited David with tens of thousands," he thought, "but me with only thousands. What more can he get but the kingdom?"
091Sm 18:9 And from that time on Saul kept a jealous eye on David.
091Sm 18:10 The next day an evil spirit from God came forcefully upon Saul. He was prophesying in his house, while David was playing the harp, as he usually did. Saul had a spear in his hand
091Sm 18:11 and he hurled it, saying to himself, "I'll pin David to the wall." But David eluded him twice.
091Sm 18:12 Saul was afraid of David, because the LORD was with David but had left Saul.
091Sm 18:13 So he sent David away from him and gave him command over a thousand men, and David led the troops in their campaigns.
091Sm 18:14 In everything he did he had great success, because the LORD was with him.
091Sm 18:15 When Saul saw how successful he was, he was afraid of him.
