091Sm 25:26 "Now since the LORD has kept you, my master, from bloodshed and from avenging yourself with your own hands, as surely as the LORD lives and as you live, may your enemies and all who intend to harm my master be like Nabal.
091Sm 25:27 And let this gift, which your servant has brought to my master, be given to the men who follow you.
091Sm 25:28 Please forgive your servant's offense, for the LORD will certainly make a lasting dynasty for my master, because he fights the LORD'S battles. Let no wrongdoing be found in you as long as you live.
091Sm 25:29 Even though someone is pursuing you to take your life, the life of my master will be bound securely in the bundle of the living by the LORD your God. But the lives of your enemies he will hurl away as from the pocket of a sling.
091Sm 25:30 When the LORD has done for my master every good thing he promised concerning him and has appointed him leader over Israel,
091Sm 25:31 my master will not have on his conscience the staggering burden of needless bloodshed or of having avenged himself. And when the LORD has brought my master success, remember your servant."
091Sm 25:32 David said to Abigail, "Praise be to the LORD, the God of Israel, who has sent you today to meet me.
091Sm 25:33 May you be blessed for your good judgment and for keeping me from bloodshed this day and from avenging myself with my own hands.
091Sm 25:34 Otherwise, as surely as the LORD, the God of Israel, lives, who has kept me from harming you, if you had not come quickly to meet me, not one male belonging to Nabal would have been left alive by daybreak."
091Sm 25:35 Then David accepted from her hand what she had brought him and said, "Go home in peace. I have heard your words and granted your request."
091Sm 25:36 When Abigail went to Nabal, he was in the house holding a banquet like that of a king. He was in high spirits and very drunk. So she told him nothing until daybreak.
091Sm 25:37 Then in the morning, when Nabal was sober, his wife told him all these things, and his heart failed him and he became like a stone.
091Sm 25:38 About ten days later, the LORD struck Nabal and he died.
091Sm 25:39 When David heard that Nabal was dead, he said, "Praise be to the LORD, who has upheld my cause against Nabal for treating me with contempt. He has kept his servant from doing wrong and has brought Nabal's wrongdoing down on his own head." Then David sent word to Abigail, asking her to become his wife.
091Sm 25:40 His servants went to Carmel and said to Abigail, "David has sent us to you to take you to become his wife."
091Sm 25:41 She bowed down with her face to the ground and said, "Here is your maidservant, ready to serve you and wash the feet of my master's servants."
091Sm 25:42 Abigail quickly got on a donkey and, attended by her five maids, went with David's messengers and became his wife.
091Sm 25:43 David had also married Ahinoam of Jezreel, and they both were his wives.
091Sm 25:44 But Saul had given his daughter Michal, David's wife, to Paltiel son of Laish, who was from Gallim.
091Sm 26:1 The Ziphites went to Saul at Gibeah and said, "Is not David hiding on the hill of Hakilah, which faces Jeshimon?"
091Sm 26:2 So Saul went down to the Desert of Ziph, with his three thousand chosen men of Israel, to search there for David.
091Sm 26:3 Saul made his camp beside the road on the hill of Hakilah facing Jeshimon, but David stayed in the desert. When he saw that Saul had followed him there,
091Sm 26:4 he sent out scouts and learned that Saul had definitely arrived.
091Sm 26:5 Then David set out and went to the place where Saul had camped. He saw where Saul and Abner son of Ner, the commander of the army, had lain down. Saul was lying inside the camp, with the army encamped around him.
091Sm 26:6 David then asked Ahimelech the Hittite and Abishai son of Zeruiah, Joab's brother, "Who will go down into the camp with me to Saul?" "I'll go with you," said Abishai.
091Sm 26:7 So David and Abishai went to the army by night, and there was Saul, lying asleep inside the camp with his spear stuck in the ground near his head. Abner and the soldiers were lying around him.
091Sm 26:8 Abishai said to David, "Today God has delivered your enemy into your hands. Now let me pin him to the ground with one thrust of my spear; I won't strike him twice."
091Sm 26:9 But David said to Abishai, "Don't destroy him! Who can lay a hand on the LORD'S anointed and be guiltless?
091Sm 26:10 As surely as the LORD lives," he said, "the LORD himself will strike him; either his time will come and he will die, or he will go into battle and perish.
091Sm 26:11 But the LORD forbid that I should lay a hand on the LORD'S anointed. Now get the spear and water jug that are near his head, and let's go."
091Sm 26:12 So David took the spear and water jug near Saul's head, and they left. No one saw or knew about it, nor did anyone wake up. They were all sleeping, because the LORD had put them into a deep sleep.
091Sm 26:13 Then David crossed over to the other side and stood on top of the hill some distance away; there was a wide space between them.
091Sm 26:14 He called out to the army and to Abner son of Ner, "Aren't you going to answer me, Abner?" Abner replied, "Who are you who calls to the king?"
091Sm 26:15 David said, "You're a man, aren't you? And who is like you in Israel? Why didn't you guard your lord the king? Someone came to destroy your lord the king.
091Sm 26:16 What you have done is not good. As surely as the LORD lives, you and your men deserve to die, because you did not guard your master, the LORD'S anointed. Look around you. Where are the king's spear and water jug that were near his head?"
091Sm 26:17 Saul recognized David's voice and said, "Is that your voice, David my son?" David replied, "Yes it is, my lord the king."
091Sm 26:18 And he added, "Why is my lord pursuing his servant? What have I done, and what wrong am I guilty of?
091Sm 26:19 Now let my lord the king listen to his servant's words. If the LORD has incited you against me, then may he accept an offering. If, however, men have done it, may they be cursed before the LORD! They have now driven me from my share in the LORD'S inheritance and have said, 'Go, serve other gods.'
091Sm 26:20 Now do not let my blood fall to the ground far from the presence of the LORD. The king of Israel has come out to look for a flea--as one hunts a partridge in the mountains."
091Sm 26:21 Then Saul said, "I have sinned. Come back, David my son. Because you considered my life precious today, I will not try to harm you again. Surely I have acted like a fool and have erred greatly."
091Sm 26:22 "Here is the king's spear," David answered. "Let one of your young men come over and get it.
091Sm 26:23 The LORD rewards every man for his righteousness and faithfulness. The LORD delivered you into my hands today, but I would not lay a hand on the LORD'S anointed.
091Sm 26:24 As surely as I valued your life today, so may the LORD value my life and deliver me from all trouble."
091Sm 26:25 Then Saul said to David, "May you be blessed, my son David; you will do great things and surely triumph." So David went on his way, and Saul returned home.
091Sm 27:1 But David thought to himself, "One of these days I will be destroyed by the hand of Saul. The best thing I can do is to escape to the land of the Philistines. Then Saul will give up searching for me anywhere in Israel, and I will slip out of his hand."
091Sm 27:2 So David and the six hundred men with him left and went over to Achish son of Maoch king of Gath.
091Sm 27:3 David and his men settled in Gath with Achish. Each man had his family with him, and David had his two wives£º Ahinoam of Jezreel and Abigail of Carmel, the widow of Nabal.
091Sm 27:4 When Saul was told that David had fled to Gath, he no longer searched for him.
091Sm 27:5 Then David said to Achish, "If I have found favor in your eyes, let a place be assigned to me in one of the country towns, that I may live there. Why should your servant live in the royal city with you?"
091Sm 27:6 So on that day Achish gave him Ziklag, and it has belonged to the kings of Judah ever since.
091Sm 27:7 David lived in Philistine territory a year and four months.
091Sm 27:8 Now David and his men went up and raided the Geshurites, the Girzites and the Amalekites. (From ancient times these peoples had lived in the land extending to Shur and Egypt.)
091Sm 27:9 Whenever David attacked an area, he did not leave a man or woman alive, but took sheep and cattle, donkeys and camels, and clothes. Then he returned to Achish.
091Sm 27:10 When Achish asked, "Where did you go raiding today?" David would say, "Against the Negev of Judah" or "Against the Negev of Jerahmeel" or "Against the Negev of the Kenites."
091Sm 27:11 He did not leave a man or woman alive to be brought to Gath, for he thought, "They might inform on us and say, 'This is what David did.'" And such was his practice as long as he lived in Philistine territory.
091Sm 27:12 Achish trusted David and said to himself, "He has become so odious to his people, the Israelites, that he will be my servant forever."
091Sm 28:1 In those days the Philistines gathered their forces to fight against Israel. Achish said to David, "You must understand that you and your men will accompany me in the army."
091Sm 28:2 David said, "Then you will see for yourself what your servant can do." Achish replied, "Very well, I will make you my bodyguard for life."
091Sm 28:3 Now Samuel was dead, and all Israel had mourned for him and buried him in his own town of Ramah. Saul had expelled the mediums and spiritists from the land.
091Sm 28:4 The Philistines assembled and came and set up camp at Shunem, while Saul gathered all the Israelites and set up camp at Gilboa.
091Sm 28:5 When Saul saw the Philistine army, he was afraid; terror filled his heart.
091Sm 28:6 He inquired of the LORD, but the LORD did not answer him by dreams or Urim or prophets.
091Sm 28:7 Saul then said to his attendants, "Find me a woman who is a medium, so I may go and inquire of her." "There is one in Endor," they said.
091Sm 28:8 So Saul disguised himself, putting on other clothes, and at night he and two men went to the woman. "Consult a spirit for me," he said, "and bring up for me the one I name."
091Sm 28:9 But the woman said to him, "Surely you know what Saul has done. He has cut off the mediums and spiritists from the land. Why have you set a trap for my life to bring about my death?"
091Sm 28:10 Saul swore to her by the LORD, "As surely as the LORD lives, you will not be punished for this."
091Sm 28:11 Then the woman asked, "Whom shall I bring up for you?" "Bring up Samuel," he said.
091Sm 28:12 When the woman saw Samuel, she cried out at the top of her voice and said to Saul, "Why have you deceived me? You are Saul!"
091Sm 28:13 The king said to her, "Don't be afraid. What do you see?" The woman said, "I see a spirit coming up out of the ground."
091Sm 28:14 "What does he look like?" he asked. "An old man wearing a robe is coming up," she said. Then Saul knew it was Samuel, and he bowed down and prostrated himself with his face to the ground.
091Sm 28:15 Samuel said to Saul, "Why have you disturbed me by bringing me up?" "I am in great distress," Saul said. "The Philistines are fighting against me, and God has turned away from me. He no longer answers me, either by prophets or by dreams. So I have called on you to tell me what to do."
091Sm 28:16 Samuel said, "Why do you consult me, now that the LORD has turned away from you and become your enemy?
091Sm 28:17 The LORD has done what he predicted through me. The LORD has torn the kingdom out of your hands and given it to one of your neighbors--to David.
091Sm 28:18 Because you did not obey the LORD or carry out his fierce wrath against the Amalekites, the LORD has done this to you today.
091Sm 28:19 The LORD will hand over both Israel and you to the Philistines, and tomorrow you and your sons will be with me. The LORD will also hand over the army of Israel to the Philistines."
091Sm 28:20 Immediately Saul fell full length on the ground, filled with fear because of Samuel's words. His strength was gone, for he had eaten nothing all that day and night.
091Sm 28:21 When the woman came to Saul and saw that he was greatly shaken, she said, "Look, your maidservant has obeyed you. I took my life in my hands and did what you told me to do.
091Sm 28:22 Now please listen to your servant and let me give you some food so you may eat and have the strength to go on your way."
091Sm 28:23 He refused and said, "I will not eat." But his men joined the woman in urging him, and he listened to them. He got up from the ground and sat on the couch.
091Sm 28:24 The woman had a fattened calf at the house, which she butchered at once. She took some flour, kneaded it and baked bread without yeast.
091Sm 28:25 Then she set it before Saul and his men, and they ate. That same night they got up and left.
091Sm 29:1 The Philistines gathered all their forces at Aphek, and Israel camped by the spring in Jezreel.
